---
title: "GPUpgrade | Methodology"
---
{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}

{% block content %}
<section class="hero">
  <div class="hero-container">
    <div class="hero-content">
      <h1 class="hero-title">
        Performance Rating
        <span class="hero-title-accent">Methodology</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Understanding how we calculate and adjust GPU performance scores across different resolutions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="methodology-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="methodology-content">

      <!-- Overview -->
      <div class="methodology-block">
        <h2 class="section-title methodology">Overview</h2>
        <p class="methodology-text">
          For each benchmark, every graphics card receives a score from 0 to 100, calculated as a percentage relative to
          the top performer in that specific benchmark. Our methodology combines pure raster performance data with
          practical considerations like VRAM capacity and modern GPU features.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Raw Performance Calculations -->
      <div class="methodology-block">
        <h2 class="section-title methodology">Raw Performance Calculations</h2>
        <p class="methodology-text">
          The <strong>raw performance rating</strong> represents pure raster performance without upscaling or ray
          tracing, based on data from eight different 3DMark benchmarks and TechPowerUp performance rankings. Each
          resolution category uses a different weighting formula:
        </p>

        <div class="formula-grid">
          <div class="formula-card">
            <h3 class="formula-title">Overall Performance</h3>
            <div class="formula-content">
              <p class="formula-text">
                (TPU × 2) + Fire Strike Ultra + Wild Life Extreme + Night Raid + Firestrike + Steel Nomad (DX12) + Steel
                Nomad Light (DX12) + Time Spy + Time Spy Extreme
              </p>
              <p class="formula-divisor">÷ 10</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="formula-card">
            <h3 class="formula-title">1080p Performance</h3>
            <div class="formula-content">
              <p class="formula-text">
                TPU + Night Raid + (Fire Strike × 2.5) + (Time Spy ÷ 2)
              </p>
              <p class="formula-divisor">÷ 5</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="formula-card">
            <h3 class="formula-title">1440p Performance</h3>
            <div class="formula-content">
              <p class="formula-text">
                TPU + (Steel Nomad Light × 1.5) + (Time Spy × 2) + (Port Royal ÷ 2)
              </p>
              <p class="formula-divisor">÷ 5</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="formula-card">
            <h3 class="formula-title">4K Performance</h3>
            <div class="formula-content">
              <p class="formula-text">
                (TPU × 2) + Fire Strike Ultra + Wild Life Extreme + Steel Nomad + Time Spy Extreme
              </p>
              <p class="formula-divisor">÷ 6</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- VRAM Adjustments -->
      <div class="methodology-block">
        <h2 class="section-title methodology">VRAM Adjustments</h2>
        <p class="methodology-text">
          The raw performance score is first adjusted to account for VRAM limitations, as cards with insufficient VRAM
          may experience performance degradation in modern games. This adjustment penalizes cards with less than 16GB of
          VRAM:
        </p>

        <div class="adjustment-grid">
          <div class="adjustment-card">
            <h4 class="adjustment-title">Overall</h4>
            <p class="adjustment-formula">
              (Score × 5) + ((Score × min(VRAM, 13)) ÷ 13) ÷ 6
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="adjustment-card">
            <h4 class="adjustment-title">1080p</h4>
            <p class="adjustment-formula">
              (Score × 6) + ((Score × min(VRAM, 12.5)) ÷ 12.5) ÷ 7
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="adjustment-card">
            <h4 class="adjustment-title">1440p</h4>
            <p class="adjustment-formula">
              (Score × 4) + ((Score × min(VRAM, 13)) ÷ 13) ÷ 5
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="adjustment-card">
            <h4 class="adjustment-title">4K</h4>
            <p class="adjustment-formula">
              (Score × 4) + ((Score × min(VRAM, 13.5)) ÷ 13.5) ÷ 5
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Features & Functionality -->
      <div class="methodology-block">
        <h2 class="section-title methodology">Features & Functionality Multipliers</h2>
        <p class="methodology-text">
          After VRAM adjustment, scores are further modified based on modern GPU features and capabilities. These
          multipliers vary by resolution to reflect real-world usage patterns:
        </p>

        <div class="features-grid">
          <div class="feature-card">
            <h4 class="feature-title">Upscaling Technology</h4>
            <div class="feature-content">
              <p class="feature-weight">Weight: 10</p>
              <p class="feature-desc">Blackwell DLSS SR (best) to FSR 2 SR (baseline)</p>
              <div class="feature-adjustments">
                <span class="adjustment-tag">1080p: Not considered</span>
                <span class="adjustment-tag">1440p: Half weight</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="feature-card">
            <h4 class="feature-title">Frame Generation</h4>
            <div class="feature-content">
              <p class="feature-weight">Weight: 4</p>
              <p class="feature-desc">DLSS 4 MFG (best) to no frame generation (baseline)</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="feature-card">
            <h4 class="feature-title">I/O Bandwidth</h4>
            <div class="feature-content">
              <p class="feature-weight">Weight: 3</p>
              <p class="feature-desc">DP 2.1 UHBR20 (80 Gbps) to DP 1.2 HBR2 (21.6 Gbps)</p>
              <div class="feature-adjustments">
                <span class="adjustment-tag">1080p: Half weight</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="feature-card">
            <h4 class="feature-title">Hardware Ray Tracing</h4>
            <div class="feature-content">
              <p class="feature-weight">Weight: 8</p>
              <p class="feature-desc">Nvidia Blackwell (best) to no hardware RT (baseline)</p>
              <div class="feature-adjustments">
                <span class="adjustment-tag">1440p: Not considered</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="feature-card">
            <h4 class="feature-title">Driver Support</h4>
            <div class="feature-content">
              <p class="feature-weight">Weight: 4</p>
              <p class="feature-desc">Full support (best) to legacy/extended support (reduced)</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Resolution-Specific Notes -->
      <div class="methodology-block">
        <h2 class="section-title methodology">Resolution-Specific Adjustments</h2>
        <div class="resolution-notes">
          <div class="resolution-note">
            <h4 class="note-title">1080p Considerations</h4>
            <p class="note-text">
              Upscaling technologies are not factored in, as native 1080p performance is typically sufficient. I/O
              bandwidth receives half weight since high refresh rate limitations are less critical at this resolution.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="resolution-note">
            <h4 class="note-title">1440p Considerations</h4>
            <p class="note-text">
              Upscaling receives half weight as it becomes more relevant but not critical. Ray tracing is not separately
              weighted since Port Royal benchmark data already incorporates RT performance.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="resolution-note">
            <h4 class="note-title">4K Considerations</h4>
            <p class="note-text">
              All feature multipliers are applied at full weight, reflecting the demanding nature of 4K gaming where
              every advantage becomes crucial for playable performance.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Final Note -->
      <div class="methodology-block">
        <div class="disclaimer-card">
          <h3 class="disclaimer-title">Methodology Notes</h3>
          <p class="disclaimer-text">
            The weighting assigned to each factor will always be somewhat subjective and dependent on individual use
            cases. Our approach aims to be as methodical and factually grounded as possible, balancing raw performance
            with practical considerations that affect real-world gaming experience.
          </p>
          <p class="disclaimer-text">
            Benchmark data is sourced from 3DMark test suites and TechPowerUp's comprehensive GPU database, ensuring
            consistent and reliable performance measurements across all tested graphics cards.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}
